name: Germán Fleitas Beroes
comments: He started practicing the art of poetry at a very young age. He founded a night school in Camaguán with other people and was a volunteer teacher who taught and mentored many modest people. In 1955 he published his first collection of poems entitled “Tolvaneras”, followed by “Pásame acá la guitarra”, “Estrellas y candiles” (Romancero del llano), “Cien coplas” and “Arpa que rinde el sueño” among other publications. He wrote for Juan Vicente Torrealba lyrics of songs that are today icons of Llanera music: La Llanura, San Fernando, Guayabo Negro, Madrugada Llanera, Mi Pasaje, Sueño Llanero... are just examples of his extensive work as a composer . He also stood out as a poet, demonstrating his extensive knowledge of Venezuela's history and its customs.

name: Mrs. Edward Gallagher
comments: Born Catherine Marion Scott in Enfield near Halifax, Nova Scotia. She earned a teaching certificate when she was just sixteen. As she was too young to teach, she earned another certificate during the next year, but when she was still not allowed to teach because of her age, she moved to New York and worked as a cook in a hotel before returning to Nova Scotia to teach. Eventually teaching took Catherine back to Ketch Harbour, Nova Scotia, where she met and married Edward Gallagher, descendent of a long line of fishermen. In 1929, Edward, a World War I veteran, took over his father's duties as keeper of the Chebucto Head lighthouse. Catherine learned many folksongs from her mother, and in 1943 Dr. Helen Creighton visited her at Chebucto Head to record a few sea songs and ballads. After Dr. Creighton publicized her singing, Catherine performed on the radio and gave concerts for several years. Many of the records made at the lighthouse can be found in the Library of Congress in Washington, D.C.

name: Piero Coppola
comments: He studied at the Milan Conservatory, graduating in piano and composition in 1910. By 1911 he was already conducting opera at La Scala opera house in Milan. He then worked in Brussels, Belgium before spending the duration of World War I in Scandinavia. In 1921 he resided in London and he later moved to France. Between 1923 and 1934 he was the artistic director of La Voix de son Maître, the French branch of The Gramophone Company. In the late 1920s and 1930s Coppola conducted recordings of many works of Debussy and Ravel, including the first recordings of Debussy's La mer and Ravel's Boléro. From 1939 onwards he worked in Lausanne, Switzerland, where he died.

comments: Lynn Anthony Anselmo was married to (Little) Lynn Marie Anselmo, (born January 20, 1946  and deceased on October 25, 2021). Despite his damaged hearing, caused by pounding metal as a welder, Lynn Anthony Anselmo was a professional musician and songwriter. He ran from 1974 on, until his retirement, Tony’s Tavern, a locus for Baton Rouge singer-songwriters throughout the eighties and went solo.
